content.problemStatement:
In C programming, **code blocks** are enclosed within curly braces `{ }`. They are used to group multiple statements together and help define the structure of your program clearly. While the compiler doesn’t require indentation, using proper formatting greatly improves readability.

Code blocks are especially useful in **functions**, **loops**, and **conditional statements**, allowing multiple instructions to be treated as a single unit of execution. They also define the **scope** of variables—anything declared inside a block is accessible only within that block.

 **Syntax:**

```c
{
    // Statements inside the block
}
```

---

 **Example:**

```c
#include  // Include the standard I/O library

int main() {
    {
        // Start of a block
        printf("This is a block!"); // Print a message inside the block
        // End of the block
    }
    // Code outside the block would run after this
    return 0;
}
```

 **Expected Output:**

```default
This is a block!
```

